:["Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt","Increased fluid intake","Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","Aminoglycoside antibiotics","High protein diet"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with refractory ascites, \u003Cstrong\u003Etransjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS)\u003C/strong\u003E creates a connection between the portal and systemic circulation, reducing portal pressure and improving ascites. This procedure is considered after failure of medical management with diuretics and sodium restriction.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased fluid intake\u003C/strong\u003E is not beneficial and may worsen fluid retention. \u003Cstrong\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/strong\u003E are contraindicated as they can impair renal function and increase sodium retention. \u003Cstrong\u003EAminoglycoside antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are nephrotoxic and should be avoided. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh protein diet\u003C/strong\u003E alone does not treat ascites, though adequate nutrition is important for overall management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Portal hypertension leads to ascites through increased hydrostatic pressure and sodium retention","Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS) reduces portal pressure and improves ascites","Diuretics and sodium restriction are first-line treatments for ascites"],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. 